Priority activities include prevention of diseases caused by Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae type b, Helicobacter pylori, methicillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus, and respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), as well as control of viral hepatitis and botulism. AIP conducts infectious diseases surveillance, provides and evaluates prevention services, and conducts applied research in collaboration with other programs within CDC and with the Alaska State Division of Public Health, Alaska Native Tribal Health Consortium, Native Health Corporations, Indian Health Service, foreign ministries of health, industry, and universities. MERGE (prog3:`Program`{`id`:'P3',`name`:'BioSense Program',`fullName`:'BioSense Program',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'The BioSense Program was created by congressional mandate as part of the Public Health Security and Bioterrorism Preparedness and Response Act of 2002, and it was launched by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 2003. BioSense is a near real-time surveillance system that receives and processes electronic healthcare encounter data, including, chief complaints, final diagnosis codes, procedure codes, clinical laboratory, pharmacy prescription, and patient demographic data from participating public health jurisdictions’ non-federal hospital emergency departments and inpatient facilities in addition to all United States Department of Defense (DoD) and Veterans Affairs (VA) outpatient hospitals and clinics nationwide. The BioSense Program also receives pharmacy data from a private sector health information exchange firm and laboratory data from two national level private sector clinical laboratories. The BioSense Program is in the process of transitioning from the original BioSense application to the BioSense 2.0 application that has new governance, a new organizational structure, and a new process for data submission and management. The Association of State and Territorial Health Officials (ASTHO) has been funded through a cooperative agreement with CDC’s Division of Notifiable Disease and Healthcare Information (DNDHI) within the Public Health Surveillance and Informatics Program Office (PHSIPO) of the Office of Surveillance, Epidemiology, and Laboratory Services (OSELS) to facilitate the governance of BioSense 2.0, and through a contract with a vendor, ASTHO will offer access and use of BioSense 2.0 on a voluntary basis to state, local, and territorial health jurisdictions. Unlike the BioSense 1.0 application where participating organizations’ data were processed and stored at CDC in the CDC owned and operated Information Technology Services Office’s Mid-Tier Data Center on secure servers, all data submitted by users in BioSense 2.0 will reside in a cloud-enabled, web-based platform that sits in the secure, private Government Cloud and is in compliance with the Federal Information Security Management Act. The platform will provide users with an exclusive secure space as well as tools for posting, receiving, controlling, analyzing, and sharing their public health surveillance information with other public health jurisdictions, CDC, or other public health partners. The public health jurisdiction will retain ownership of any data it contributes to its exclusive secure space within BioSense 2.0.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/BioSense/',`operationalStatus`:'Partially Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2003',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'Boston Public Health Commission, county of Sacramento, Denver Health & Hopital Authority, H&H Corp-Marion county, New York/HRI, Tarrant county, TX',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers, Health Information Exchanges, Private Laboratories , Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Tribal Health Departments',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return prog3;

MERGE (prog8:`Program`{`id`:'P8',`name`:'Emerging Infections Program',`fullName`:'Emerging Infections Program',`shortName`:'EIP',`purpose`:'EIP is a major cooperative agreement program that supports a network of 10 state health departments (CA, CO, CT, GA, MD, MN, NM, NY, OR, TN) and their collaborators in local health departments, academic institutions, other federal agencies, and public health and clinical laboratories. EIP also supports infection control professionals and healthcare providers. The EIP aims to prevent and control infectious diseases by providing the highest quality scientific information to monitor emerging problems, evaluate public health interventions, transfer what is learned to the public health community, and inform policy. The EIP network aims to be a national resource for surveillance, prevention, and control of emerging infectious diseases. EIP activities  beyond the routine functions of health departments in ways that allow important public health questions to be answered by addressing the most important issues in infectious diseases and selecting projects that the EIP network is particularly suited to investigate, by maintaining sufficient flexibility for emergency response and addressing new problems as they arise by developing, evaluating, and ultimately transferring what is learned to public health agencies, by incorporating training as a key function of EIP activities, and by giving high priority to projects that lead directly to the prevention of disease. MERGE (prog10:`Program`{`id`:'P10',`name`:'Epidemiology and Laboratory Capacity for Infectious Diseases Cooperative Agreement',`fullName`:'Epidemiology and Laboratory Capacity for Infectious Diseases Cooperative Agreement',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'In 1994, CDC began working with other federal agencies, state and local health departments, and other partners to strengthen our nation\'s capacity to recognize and respond to emerging infectious disease threats through implementation of the CDC plan, Addressing Emerging Infectious Disease Threats: A Prevention Strategy for the United States. Although this effort is well underway, fulfilling CDC\'s vision of a safer world in the next millennium requires long-term commitment and sustained effort. The second phase of the CDC effort, Preventing Emerging Infectious Diseases: A Strategy for the 21st Century (available on the Internet at http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00054779.htm), was released in October 1998. It takes into account recent challenges and builds on the experience, success, and knowledge gained from the initial plan. The purpose of the Epidemiology and Laboratory Capacity for Infectious Diseases (ELC) program is to build on this effort by assisting state and eligible local public health agencies to strengthen their basic epidemiologic and laboratory capacity to address infectious disease threats. The ELC program focuses on notifiable diseases, food-, water-, and vector-borne diseases, vaccine-preventable diseases, and drug-resistant infections. It is intended to support activities that enhance the ability of a program to: a) identify and monitor the occurrence of infectious diseases of public health importance in a community; b) characterize disease determinants; c) identify and respond to disease outbreaks and other infectious disease emergencies; d) use public health data for priority setting and policy development; f) assess the effectiveness of activities; g) Strengthening collaboration between laboratory and epidemiology practice is a crucial component of this program.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/ncpdcid/deiss/elc.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1995',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'jurisdictions with populations >=1.5 million',`dataProviders-Manual`:'Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'Federal Government Agencies, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return prog10;

MERGE (prog18:`Program`{`id`:'P18',`name`:'HIV Drug Resistance',`fullName`:'HIV Drug Resistance',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'Surveillance of transmitted HIV drug resistance (HIVDR) and HIVDR emerging during treatment and also of antiretroviral treatment (ART) program factors associated with the emergence/prevention of HIVDR during treatment. Countries form HIVDR working groups generally based at the Ministry of Health. There are five surveillance elements: 1. HIVDR Early Warning Indicators (EWI) -- all ART sites, or representative ART sites, are surveyed annually for factors associated with HIVDR emergence/prevention: A. ART prescribing practices; B. Percentage of patients lost to follow-up after one year following ART start C. Retention on first-line ART at one year; D. Percentage of ART patients picking up their drugs on-time; E. Percentage of ART patients keeping their appointments on time F. Percentage of months in which there are no ART drug stock-outs. Sample size is calculated based on numbers of ART patients at the site. Targets are recommended; countries may select more stringent targets. 2. Monitoring of HIVDR prevention and associated factors at sentinel ART sites: HIVDR working groups select three - 15 sentinel sites annually and do baseline genotypes and endpoint genotypes on patients starting ART, and abstract other information from medical records associated with HIVDR prevention. 3. HIVDR transmission surveys: These surveys are each focused in one geographic area of the country and use a binominal sequential sampling technique which classifies prevalence of transmitted drug resistance for each of the three ART drug classes used in resource-limited countries as above or below two thresholds: 5% and 15%. 4. Cross-sectional surveys: A representative cross-section of ART patients on first-line ART are surveyed for viral load, and if the viral load is detectable (=ART failure), the specimen is genotyped to evaluate the resistance pattern. 5. Pediatric surveillance of initial HIVDR in children < =18 months of age: Remnant dried blood spots used for pediatric HIV diagnosis are genotyped for children who are HIV-positive, prevention-of-mother to child transmission (PMTCT) information is collected (which regimens received by child and mother) to evaluate resistance patterns associated with PMTCT and also for those children whose PMTCT status is recorded as \"unknown\". Information is used for public health action to change ART program practices at site and national level. The program also includes HIVDR prevention elements (training), a database into which survey data can be entered, a lab training and accreditation system for surveillance genotyping.',`webResource`:'http://www.who.int/hiv/topics/drugresistance/en/index.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2005',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Schools / Universities',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Schools / Universities',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return prog18;

LMBP extends the systematic, transparent and consistent approach to making evidence-based recommendations to the specialty of laboratory medicine consistent with standards within health care.. The LMBPTM initiative convenes laboratory medicine, health care, and evidence review experts to provide informed analyses and formulate effective recommendations. Through this program, a standardized evidence-based method1 has been developed to link LMBP recommendations to improved patient and health outcomes.  This is achieved through collaboration with diverse stakeholder organizations and partners. The CDC has funded this initiative which features the operation of the Laboratory Medicine Best Practices interactive website (www.futurelabmedicine.org) which includes participant registration to review recommendations, ongoing evidence reviews, suggestions for new and existing reviews, and to submit their own quality improvement study data which may be considered for inclusion in evidence reviews. MERGE (prog24:`Program`{`id`:'P24',`name`:'Laboratory Response Network Program',`fullName`:'Laboratory Response Network Program',`shortName`:'LRN',`purpose`:'The Laboratory Response Network (LRN) is an alliance of national and international laboratories that have formed a network to provide rapid response to biological threats, chemical threats, and other public health emergencies. The LRN establishes formal links among federal, state, and local public health laboratories, veterinary, agriculture, military, law enforcement, and water-and food-testing laboratories. Member labs include national, reference and sentinel (typically hospital-based) labs. Funding provided for the LRN enables state and local public health laboratories to renovate facilities to comply with strict safety and containment standards; purchase state-of-the art testing equipment; hire and train laboratorians; and obtain supplies necessary to perform lab tests developed by the LRN. In exchange for funding member labs must meet specific membership requirements and pass rigorous proficiency tests demonstrating their ability to accurately identify agents of concern. MERGE (prog39:`Program`{`id`:'P39',`name`:'Vaccine Safety Datalink Project',`fullName`:'Vaccine Safety Datalink Project',`shortName`:'VSD',`purpose`:'The Vaccine Safety Datalink (VSD) project is a collaborative effort between CDC\'s Immunization Safety Office and eight large managed care organizations (MCO). The VSD project was established in 1990 to monitor immunization safety and address the gaps in scientific knowledge about rare and serious adverse events following immunization. The VSD project includes a large linked database that uses administrative data sources at each MCO. Each participating site gathers data on vaccination (vaccine type, date of vaccination, concurrent vaccinations), medical outcomes (outpatient visits, inpatient visits, urgent care visits), birth data, and census data. The VSD project allows for planned immunization safety studies as well as timely investigations of hypotheses that arise from review of medical literature, reports to the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS), changes in immunization schedules, or the introduction of new vaccines. The objectives of VSD are to conduct population based research on immunization safety questions; to evaluate immunization safety hypotheses that arise from medical literature, passive surveillance systems, adjustments to immunization schedules, and introduction of new vaccines; to guide national immunization policy decisions; and to partner with healthcare providers, public health officials, and others to ensure the public has the best available information regarding the risks and benefits of immunizations.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/vaccinesafety/Activities/VSD.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1991',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'Local Managed Care Organizations',`dataProviders-Manual`:'Healthcare Providers',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Healthcare Providers',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return prog39;

ABCs is an active laboratory- and population-based surveillance system for invasive bacterial pathogens of public health importance. For each case of invasive disease in the surveillance population, a case report form with basic demographic information is completed and bacterial isolates are sent to CDC and other reference laboratories for additional laboratory evaluation. ABCs also provides an infrastructure for further public health research, including special studies aiming at identifying risk factors for disease, post-licensure evaluation of vaccine efficacy and monitoring effectiveness of prevention policies.  ABCs was initially established in four states in 1995. It currently operates among 10 EIP sites across the United States, representing a population of approximately 42 million persons. At this time, ABCs conducts surveillance for six pathogens: group A and group B Streptococcus (GAS, GBS), Haemophilus influenzae, Neisseria meningitidis, Streptococcus pneumoniae, and methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA). Additionally, surveillance for legionellosis and enhanced surveillance for pertussis has been ongoing since 2011. The program objective is to build state capacity to initiate, expand, or improve adult blood lead surveillance programs which can accurately measure trends in adult blood lead levels and which can effectively intervene to prevent lead over-exposures.   The public health objective of the ABLES program is identical to the Occupational Safety and Health objective 7 in Healthy People 2020, which is to reduce the rate of adults (age 16 or older) who have blood lead levels (BLL) equal or greater than ten micrograms per deciliter (BLLs ≥10 µg/dL). MERGE (ssys7:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS7',`name`:'Aggregate Hospitalization and Death Reporting Activity',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'AHDRA',`purpose`:'The Aggregate Hospitalizations and Deaths Reporting Activity (AHDRA) is a web-based influenza surveillance system implemented in response to the 2009 H1N1 pandemic that collects voluntary reports of influenza-related hospitalizations and deaths from U.S. states and territories. (This system does not collect reports of individual cases of flu illness, only hospitalizations and deaths.)  The primary goal of state-level reporting of influenza hospitalizations and deaths is to track the progression of influenza activity within each state and to determine trends (increasing or decreasing).   AHDRA tracks flu-related hospitalizations and deaths, not just those related to 2009 H1N1. With BioSense, health officials can exchange information faster, improve their common awareness of health threats over time and across regional boundaries, and better coordinate investigations and community actions to protect health.  BioSense 2.0 is the latest version of the BioSense system. BioSense 2.0 provides a mechanism to collect and share information on emergency department visits, hospitalizations, and other health related data from multiple sources, including the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), the Department of Defense (DoD), and civilian hospitals from around the country. As a binational effort, BIDS relies on local, state, and federal collaboration to enhance infectious disease surveillance, build border-region epidemiology and laboratory capacity, and strengthen binational communication systems to improve disease prevention. MERGE (ssys26:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS26',`name`:'Countermeasure Tracking Systems',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'CTS',`purpose`:'CTS consists of multiple interoperating components which enhance the capacity of federal, state, and local public health agencies to track and manage medical and non-medical inventory and usage to support both daily operations and all-hazards events. The four system components interoperate to improve communications and event response efficiency while still functioning independently, recognizing the unique requirements and use cases for each system. In support of close communication and linkage among the components, all four system components have a similar “look and feel” and use the same security mechanism which allows a seamless transition between systems, enhancing ease of use and supporting just-in-time training. Collectively, the data consolidated from these systems can show population coverage, numbers of untreated individuals, drug and equipment shortages, need for resupply and more. The Web-based applications are deployed centrally at CDC and use the CDC’s secure data access method for security. They are available free of charge to users.  Overview of System Components:  Inventory Management and Tracking System (IMATS)-  The IMATS solution provides state and local public health providers with a tool to track medical and non-medical countermeasure inventory and supplies during daily operations or an event. The solution tracks quantities of inventory, monitors reorder thresholds, and facilitates warehouse operations including receiving, staging, and storing of inventory.  Communications Portal (CP)-  The Communications Portal is a content management system that consolidates important event response information in one place ensuring efficient communications during an event. Such information may include Emergency Use Authorization (EUA) and Investigational New Drug (IND) information, lot recalls, and other related information and materials.  Countermeasure and Response Administration (CRA)-  CRA is an emergency preparedness and response asset useful for any event involving vaccine doses administered tracking, pharmaceuticals and medical materiel dispensing, or implementation of social distancing measures. CRA supports analysis of pharmaceutical safety, coverage, and effectiveness during an event which improves patient outcomes. CRA is a flexible all-hazards system that reduces the need for development of new applications each time there is a new event.  Countermeasure Inventory Tracking (CIT) Dashboard-  The CIT Dashboard (a.k.a. the Countermeasure Supply Chain Dashboard) is a situational awareness tool used by the Division of Strategic National Stockpile to construct a nationwide inventory supply picture. The CIT Dashboard consolidates project area inventory data reported through CRA with data from the commercial drug sector. This consolidated data forms a complete inventory supply picture which provides situational awareness during an event. Additionally, farming is one of the few industries in which family members (who often share the work and live on the premises) are also at risk for fatal and nonfatal injuries.  Youth who live on, work on, or visit farms in the United States (U.S.) have been identified as a special population at high risk for non-fatal and fatal injuries. Since 1996, NIOSH has conducted the Childhood Agricultural Injury Prevention Initiative to promote the reduction of injuries and fatalities to youth on farms in the U.S. A major component of this initiative is the development of an ongoing surveillance program to track the magnitude of non-fatal injuries occurring to all youth exposed to farm hazards.  An initial step in the development of the surveillance program was the completion of the Childhood Agricultural Injury Survey (CAIS) first conducted in 1999 for the calendar year 1998. NIOSH collaborated with the U.S. Department of Agriculture’s National Agricultural Statistics Service (USDA-NASS) to conduct this survey.  In 1990, Congress directed NIOSH to develop an extensive agricultural safety and health program to address the high risks of injuries and illnesses experienced by workers and families in agriculture. One component of this program was the development of an ongoing surveillance program to track the magnitude of nonfatal injuries occurring to adults working in agriculture.  An initial step in the development of the surveillance program was the completion of the Occupational Injury Surveillance of Production Agriculture (OISPA) survey.  This survey, first conducted for the calendar year 2001, was designed to produce national and regional estimates of the number of adults 20 years of age and older working on farms and the number of occupational injuries that these workers incur.  NIOSH collaborated with the US Department of Agriculture’s National Agricultural Statistics Service (USDA-NASS) to conduct the initial survey, as well as additional OISPA surveys for calendar years 2004 and 2009. There are guidelines from the World Health Organization, Canada, Brazil, and Australia that public health agencies can follow to make decisions about allowing access to drinking water sources and recreational areas with ongoing HABs. However, there are no U.S. federal regulations, and no official guidance from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency specifying allowable concentrations of HAB-related toxins in the water. Listeria infections (listeriosis) are nationally notifiable. Nearly all cases of listeriosis in persons who are not infants result from eating food contaminated with L. monocytogenes; newborn infants can develop listeriosis if their mother ate contaminated food during pregnancy.    The Listeria Initiative is an enhanced surveillance system that collects reports of laboratory-confirmed cases of human listeriosis in the United States. Demographic, clinical, laboratory, and epidemiologic data are collected using a standardized, extended questionnaire. The NAWS is performed under contract to the Department of Labor and its information is made available to the public through periodic research reports and a public use data set. Numerous Federal government agencies utilize NAWS findings for a multitude of purposes, including occupational injury and health surveillance, estimating the need for services, allocating program dollars to areas of greatest need, and program design and evaluation. The survey samples crop workers in three cycles each year to reflect the seasonality of agricultural production and employment. Workers are located at their farm job sites. MERGE (ssys83:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS83',`name`:'National Arboviral Surveillance System',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'ArboNet',`purpose`:'ArboNET is a national arboviral surveillance system managed by CDC and state health departments. In addition to human disease, ArboNET maintains data on arboviral infections among presumptive viremic blood donors, veterinary disease cases, mosquitoes, dead birds, and sentinel animals.  As with other national surveillance data, ArboNET data have several limitations that should be considered in analysis, interpretation, and reporting:  1.  ArboNET is a passive surveillance system. It is dependent on clinicians considering the diagnosis of an arboviral disease and obtaining the appropriate diagnostic test, and reporting of laboratory-confirmed cases to public health authorities. Diagnosis and reporting are incomplete, and the incidence of arboviral diseases is underestimated.   2.  Reported neuroinvasive disease cases are considered the most accurate indicator of arboviral activity in humans because of the substantial associated morbidity. In contrast, reported cases of nonneuroinvasive arboviral disease are more likely to be affected by disease awareness and healthcare-seek­ing behavior in different communities and by the availability and specificity of laboratory tests performed. Surveillance data for nonneuroinvasive disease should be interpreted with cau­tion and generally should not be used to make comparisons between geographic areas or over time.   3.  Provisional ArboNET data are provided to help track recent arboviral disease activity. However, these data may change substantially before they are finalized. Provisional data from the current year should not be combined with or compared to final data from previous years. Throughout the world, biomonitoring has become the standard for assessing people\'s exposure to toxic substances as well as for responding to serious environmental public health problems. Rather than estimating how much of a substance gets into people from measured environmental concentrations, our scientists have taken out the guesswork by measuring levels of chemicals that actually are in people\'s bodies. And they do so with precision, speed, and pinpoint accuracy, measuring many chemicals in a very small amount—often a teaspoon or less—of blood or urine. NBP currently measures more than 450 environmental chemicals and nutritional indicators in people. All of the methods used have been published in peer-reviewed journals so that other laboratories can use them. The principle goal of NHSN are to improve safety by creating and disseminating knowledge necessary to detect and respond to current and emerging healthcare safety threats. Healthcare-associated infections and antimicrobial resistance are major problems in US healthcare institutions. In hospitals alone, nearly 2 million patients acquire infections that contribute to more than 88,000 deaths and cost more than $4.5 billion annually. Healthcare personnel are also at risk of acquiring infection while performing duties. NHSN today, is used for infection control, healthcare worker safety, blood safety, process-of-care measurement and improvement, prevention research, mandatory public reporting and public health surveillance. NHSN has been designated the system to use by facilities electing to participate in the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) Healthcare Associated Infection (HAI) Inpatient Quality Reporting (IQR) Program, ESRD Quality Incentive Program (QIP), Long Term Care Hospital Quality Reporting (LTCHQR) Program, Inpatient Rehabilitation Facility Quality Reporting Program, PPS-Exempt Cancer Hospital Quality Reporting (PCHQR) Program and Ambulatory Surgery Centers Quality Reporting Program. As part of each program, HAI events are reported to NHSN and shared with CMS. The partnership with CMS is a step toward greater transparency of HAI data and also toward stronger accountability within the US healthcare system. It also highlights the importance of strong facility-level support for infection prevention programs and professionals. Currently 10,000 healthcare facilities are enrolled with an estimated target of an additional 5000 within the calendar year.  To support our partnership with CMS’ IQR Program, in FY14 NHSN will be enhanced to enable the reporting of MRSA Bacteremia LabID Events, C. difficile LabID Events, and Healthcare Worker Influenza Vaccinations. These changes coupled with ongoing maintenance and user support from previous implementations will span the duration of the fiscal year. Functionally, NHSN supports a manual data entry and uses pre-existing electronic data from electronic health records (EHR) and other healthcare information systems using Health Level 7 (HL7) balloted and standardized Clinical Document Architecture (CDA) documents for automated data entry. The development aspects of the project primarily supports and maintains the operations of the system and user support while integrating new feature and functionality deemed necessary by CDC’s SB/DHQP Program. On average, every 24 minutes, 57 regional Poison Centers (PCs) upload data collected from calls made to their facilities to the national poison center reporting database and system known as the National Poison Data System or NPDS. MERGE (ssys130:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS130',`name`:'Pregnancy Risk Assessment Monitoring System',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'PRAMS',`purpose`:'PRAMS, the Pregnancy Risk Assessment Monitoring System, is a surveillance project of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and state health departments. PRAMS collects state-specific, population-based data on maternal attitudes and experiences before, during, and shortly after pregnancy. PRAMS was initiated in 1987 because infant mortality rates were no longer declining as rapidly as they had in prior years. In addition, the incidence of low birth weight infants had changed little in the previous 20 years. Research has indicated that maternal behaviors during pregnancy may influence infant birth weight and mortality rates. The goal of the PRAMS project is to improve the health of mothers and infants by reducing adverse outcomes such as low birth weight, infant mortality and morbidity, and maternal morbidity. PRAMS provides state-specific data for planning and assessing health programs and for describing maternal experiences that may contribute to maternal and infant health. PRAMS provides data for state health officials to use to improve the health of mothers and infants. PRAMS allows CDC and the states to monitor changes in maternal and child health indicators (e.g., unintended pregnancy, prenatal care, breast-feeding, smoking, drinking, infant health). PRAMS enhances information from birth certificates used to plan and review state maternal and infant health programs. The PRAMS sample is chosen from all women who had a live birth recently, so findings can be applied to the state\'s entire population of women who have recently delivered a live-born infant. PRAMS not only provides state-specific data but also allows comparisons among participating states because the same data collection methods are used in all states.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/prams/',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1988',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'New York City',`dataProvidersManual`:'Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Tribal Health Departments',`dataProvidersElectronic`:'',`dataRecipientsManual`:'Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Tribal Health Departments',`dataRecipientsElectronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return ssys130;
MERGE (ssys131:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS131',`name`:'Public Health Genomics Surveillance - Coordination Activity',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'Assessing the public’s awareness and use of genomic tests and family health history through population-based surveys provides important baseline data, and helps monitors progress toward implementing evidence-based recommendations, including those underlying Healthy People 2020 objectives. Additionally, it contributes to the knowledge base that supports the development and dissemination of appropriate public health messages and educational materials for the general public and health care providers, as well as informing federal and state policy. In 2012, the CDC Office of Public Health Genomics developed a three-tiered framework for classifying genomic tests and family health history based on the availability of scientific evidence and evidence-based recommendations supporting their use. Tier 1 genomic applications are recommended for clinical use by evidence-based panels, based on systematic review of evidence of validity and utility. Tier 2 applications may be useful for informed decision making in clinical practice, based on demonstrated validity, and promising utility.  Tier 3 applications are not ready for clinical use, due to validity or utility not demonstrated, or systematic assessment finding harms outweigh benefits. States are assessing awareness and use of specific Tier 1, 2 and 3 genomic applications using state-added questions in the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS). Ethical, legal and social issues:  The potential for genetic discrimination is a concern relevant to the increased availability of genetic information associated with the increased use of genetic tests in clinical practice and in the direct-to-consumer market.  The Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act (GINA) was signed into law in 2008. While GINA is designed to protect against discrimination in health insurance coverage and employment, it does not address other areas where discrimination is possible, such as in life, disability and long-term care insurance. More information is needed on the extent that the general public is aware of protections offered under GINA, and is concerned about the potential for genetic discrimination, since these may prove to be significant factors affecting the uptake of genetic testing. MERGE (ssys141:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS141',`name`:'Search for Diabetes in Youth',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'Search',`purpose`:'In response to a growing public health concern, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the National Institutes of Health (NIH) are funding a 5-year, multicenter study, SEARCH for Diabetes in Youth, to examine the current status of diabetes among children and adolescents in the United States. The primary goals of SEARCH are 1) to develop a uniform classification of types of childhood diabetes (no \"gold standard\" definitions of types now exist) 2) to estimate the number of new (incidence) and existing (prevalence) childhood diabetes cases by type, age of the child, sex, and racial or ethnic group 3) to describe the clinical characteristics of different types of diabetes in youth and how they evolved 4) to describe the complications of diabetes in children and adolescents 5) to describe the quality of life of children and adolescents with diabetes. Six U.S. sites collaborate with CDC and NIH on SEARCH. The youth population being studied is provided by the six SEARCH sites and involves more than 5 million, or 6 percent, of all American children aged 0 to 19 years. This will be the largest and most racially and geographically diverse study group ever involved in a youth diabetes study. During the 5-year study period, the SEARCH sites will examine more than 6,000 existing cases of pediatric diabetes and about 800 new cases each year. Data collection began in 2002. With data provided by the SEARCH study, scientists can follow current cases of childhood diabetes to monitor any changes that occur in the type, characteristics, and outcomes of specific cases. The data collection of childhood diabetes cases will provide valuable information to researchers and health care providers in developing appropriate care and treatment protocols that will reduce the likelihood of complications and lessen the burden of diabetes in the daily lives of children and adolescents with diabetes.',`webResource`:'http://www.searchfordiabetes.org/',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2001',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'Cincinnati, Seattle, Southern California',`dataProvidersManual`:'Schools / Universities',`dataProvidersElectronic`:'',`dataRecipientsManual`:'',`dataRecipientsElectronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return ssys141;

MERGE (ssys145:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS145',`name`:'State Injury Indicators',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'SII',`purpose`:'The State Injury Indicators utilize data drawn from state vital statistics records, state hospital discharge data (HDD), state emergency department (ED) data, the National Center for Health Statistics’ National Vital Statistics System (NVSS), the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality’s Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project (HCUP), Nationwide Inpatient Sample (NIS) and Nationwide Emergency Department Sample (NEDS), the Youth Risk Behavior Survey (YRBS), the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS), and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration’s Fatality Analysis Reporting System (FARS). The methods used have been developed using a consensus building process working group with representatives from the Safe States Alliance, the Council of State and Territorial Epidemiologists (CSTE), the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and its National Center for Injury Prevention and Control (NCIPC), and the Society for Advancement of Violence and Injury Research (SAVIR). Methods are fully delineated in the annual State Injury Indicators: Instructions for Preparing Data manuals. In brief, injury hospitalization and emergency department cases are identified from state-based HDD  and ED data using the principal diagnosis (or first-listed ICD-9-CM diagnosis code) with other selective factors. Injury deaths are identified from vital statistics data using the ICD-10 underlying-cause-of-death codes. All multiple-cause-of-death fields are searched for the fatal TBI indicator. For comparison purposes, national rates for the fatality indicators are generated by using the NVSS. MERGE (ssys156:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS156',`name`:'Universal Data Collection',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'UDC',`purpose`:'People with hemophilia, von Willebrand disease, and other congenital bleeding disorders are at risk for recurrent bleeding episodes, which can predispose to long-term morbidity and increased mortality.   In particular, people with hemophilia are susceptible to the development of chronic, and often debilitating joint disease from repeated bleeding into major joints such as the knee and ankle.  The treatment of a bleeding episode involves the replacement of the missing protein through the intravenous administration of factor concentrate which is derived from, or contains components of human blood plasma.  As a result, people with hemophilia using these treatment products are at risk for infection with viral, blood-borne diseases such as hepatitis and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) that can be transmitted in the blood products.  Nearly 70% of all persons with hemophilia in the U.S. receive at least some of their medical care from federally-sponsored, specialized hemophilia treatment centers (HTCs) located throughout the country.  These centers currently provide care to over 27,000 children and adults with these disorders.  The purpose of the Universal Data Collection (UDC) project was to collect a uniform set of clinical data on people with hemophilia and other congenital bleeding disorders receiving care at 130+ U.S. HTCs.  These data are used to characterize the population, monitor blood and blood product safety, and identify complications.   All persons with hemophilia A or B and related congenital bleeding disorders who received care at an HTC were eligible for inclusion in the data collection effort.  Routine clinical data were collected using a combination of medical record abstraction or direct patient interview by HTC staff as a part of the routine clinical assessment. Information was recorded on standardized data collection forms or electronic data systems.  There were two parts to the data collection: patient registration and current clinical information recording.  The Registration Form was completed one time only for each patient and served to introduce the patient into the data system.  Data collected on this form includes baseline demographic and clinical information that did not change over time.  The current clinical information was collected by using the Annual Visit Form for participants 2 years old and older, and by using the Baby Visit Form for children under two years old.  The Annual Visit Form was completed for each patient ≥ 2 years old by treatment center staff at the first visit and once per year thereafter and collected detailed information on clinical outcomes concerning joint disease and viral and other complications.  The Baby Visit Form was completed by treatment center staff at the first visit and at 6 month intervals until age 2 years.  The Baby Visit Form collected information on current treatment, bleed history, and clinical outcomes.  In addition, patients were asked to complete standardized and validated age-appropriate quality of life instruments as part of the study.  Testing of serum specimens collected annually from persons receiving care in the HTCs for the presence of blood borne pathogens was offered by CDC to assist HTCs in monitoring related infections.  After testing, the remainder of each serum specimen was stored by the CDC to establish a serum bank for possible future use in evaluating the safety of blood products used by these persons. UDC data was collected annually from 1998 through September 2011. Enrollment of subjects into this project ended at the end of September 2011, but data analysis and potential testing of blood specimens is expected to continue into the foreseeable future.  Bleeding disorders surveillance has transitioned to a new project entitled “Community Counts– CDC Public Health Surveillance for Bleeding Disorders” (Community Counts).  In order to monitor complications and trends over a longer period of time, information from UDC will be linked to Community Counts where appropriate if the participant provides authorization. MERGE (ssys157:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS157',`name`:'US Outpatient Influenza-Like Illness Surveillance Network',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'ILINet',`purpose`:'The Outpatient Influenza-like Illness Surveillance Network (ILINet) consists of about 3,400 healthcare providers in 50 states reporting approximately 25 million patient visits each year. Each week, approximately 2,000 outpatient care sites around the country report data to CDC on the total number of patients seen and the number of those patients with influenza-like illness (ILI) by age group. For this system, ILI is defined as fever (temperature of 100°F [37.8°C] or greater) and a cough and/or a sore throat in the absence of a KNOWN cause other than influenza. Sites with electronic records use an equivalent definition as determined by the state public health authorities. The percentage of patient visits to healthcare providers for ILI reported each week is weighted on the basis of state population. This percentage is compared each week with the annually calculated national baseline. The baseline is the mean percentage of patient visits for ILI during non-influenza weeks for the previous three seasons plus two standard deviations. Protecting, promoting, and supporting breastfeeding, with its many known benefits for infants, children, and mothers, is a key strategy toward this goal. The Breastfeeding Report Card shows how breastfeeding is being protected, promoted, and supported in each state using five \"outcome\" and six \"process\" indicators. This allows you to make comparisons across states and indicators and work to increase breastfeeding nationwide. The five outcome indicators are derived from the breastfeeding goals outlined in Healthy People 2010, a description of the nation\'s health priorities. They profile the extent to which infants in a state are breastfed. The nine process indicators measure elements of breastfeeding-friendly communities. Each indicator is measured in every state, allowing easy state-by-state comparisons. As measures of a state\'s ability to protect, promote, and support breastfeeding, the report card indicators show where a state has been successful and where more work is needed.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/breastfeeding/data/report_card.htm',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return tool3;

The goal of the tool is to assist public health professionals in the early identification and monitoring of outbreaks of disease, as well as other public health and medical events, with emphasis on outbreaks that may indicate intentional releases of biological agents. The EARS tool facilitates creation of user-identified event/syndrome categories by which data are aggregated. MERGE (tool16:`Tool`{`id`:'TL16',`name`:'Exposure Investigation',`fullName`:'Exposure Investigation',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'An exposure investigation is one approach ATSDR uses to develop better characterization of past, current, and possible future human exposures to hazardous substances in the environment and to evaluate existing and possible health effects related to those exposures more thoroughly. There are three main ways information is gathered during an exposure investigation: Bio-medical testing (for example, urine or blood samples) is an important piece of information gathered and evaluated during an ATSDR exposure investigation. Bio-medical samples can show current (and sometimes past) exposure to a contaminant. Environmental testing (for contamination of soil, water, or air) is also an important piece of information gathered and evaluated during an exposure investigation. ATSDR investigators focus environmental testing on where people live, spend time and play, or might come in contact with contaminants under investigation. Our branch also has expertise in exposure dose reconstruction. Exposure-dose reconstruction analyses use environmental sampling information and computer models to estimate the contaminant levels that people may have been exposed to in the past or may be exposed to in the future. We can use these models to draw various conclusions. For example, how long and at what levels a drinking water well has been contaminated. We can then use the information to evaluate how a person\'s health might be affected.',`webResource`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Retired',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return tool16;

MERGE (tool28:`Tool`{`id`:'TL28',`name`:'Laboratory Response Network - Results Messenger/Results Viewer',`fullName`:'Laboratory Response Network - Results Messenger/Results Viewer',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'LRN Real Time Lab Information Exchange (RTL) project equips Laboratory Response Network (LRN) labs to securely share data with public health partners in real time according to industry standards. Its purpose is to ensure the quality and availability of LRN data and decrease the time needed to detect and respond to public health threats. The LRN is a coordinated network of public health and other laboratories for which CDC provides standard assays and protocols for testing biological and chemical terrorism agents. LRN Results Messenger (LRN RM) is a software solution created to provide LRN labs with the immediate ability to manage and share standard laboratory data. LRN RM is currently installed over 160 LRN laboratories, including 100% of the LRN’s public health labs. LRN RM provides basic laboratory data management, including the ability to enter and share sample and results data. The application enables labs to submit and respond to electronic test requests from other LRN labs, which supports the mutual assistance functionality of the LRN. The application embodies PHIN requirements and utilizes CDC’s Secure Data Network and PHIN Messaging System infrastructure. LRN Results Viewer is deployed within the CDC and provides a database to store LRN results and the ability to query and view those results. The Laboratory Information Management System Integration (LIMSi) activity is a parallel effort to LRN RM. It represents the next generation of the incremental approach to data exchange for the LRN. Its purpose is to enable laboratories to fulfill data exchange needs for the LRN using their own systems by implementing data standards and infrastructure to support Health Level 7 (HL7) messaging. LIMSi  has facilitated collaborative efforts between CDC and public health laboratory subject matter experts to refine system requirements needed to configure laboratory information management systems (LIMS) to manage LRN testing. The LIMSi project is also collaborating closely with related CDC efforts, such as the Public Health Laboratory Interoperability Project since the two efforts share many common initiatives.  Seventeen LRN laboratories have accomplished messaging of all LRN biological agents using their own systems.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/osels/phsipo/diso/LRN.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return tool28;

All programs are compliant with national standards and can be used separately or together for both routine and special data collection. Registry Plus currently includes ten applications, plus various utility programs: Abstract Plus, Web Plus, eMaRC Plus, Data File Mapper Plus, Prep Plus, Central Registry System (CRS) Plus, including Tumor Linkage and Consolidation (TLC) Plus, Link Plus, Registry Plus Online Help, EditWriter, and GenEDITS Plus. The NPCR Registry Plus suite of applications offers central cancer registries reporting solutions for all levels of data reporting sources. The online abstracting capability of Web Plus is suitable for reporting from physicians’ offices and other low-volume reporting sources, while the file upload feature can be used for electronic submission of data from all other reporting sources (often along with the offline abstraction capability of Abstract Plus). Web Plus also supports death certificate and pathology lab follow-back efforts.  eMaRC Plus can be used to receive and map electronic pathology lab files in HL7 format to NAACCR abstracts that can be processed into the central registry. Functionality to map Electronic Heath Records received in in CDA format is also currently being added to the program. The file mapping functions of the eMaRC Plus and Data File Mapper Plus tools can be used to generate follow-back files for loading into Web Plus, as well as to map files received by central registries in formats other than NAACCR-formatted files. MERGE (tool35:`Tool`{`id`:'TL35',`name`:'NIOSH Worker Health Chart Book',`fullName`:'NIOSH Worker Health Chart Book',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'The NIOSH Surveillance Program has developed a Worker Health eChartbook web site as a descriptive epidemiologic reference on occupational morbidity and mortality in the United States. It serves as a resource for agencies, organizations, employers, researchers, workers, and others who need to know about occupational injuries and illnesses. The 1st Worker Health Chartbook was prepared and published in 2000. The principal means of disseminating its content was through a type-set print document. Also, a web version (see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2000-127/) was developed, permitting the downloading of images and tables in Microsoft Excel format. The development of the 2nd Worker Health Chartbook (also see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2004-146/pdfs/2004-146.pdf) began shortly after the completion of the calendar year 2000 Worker Health Chartbook publication. From the beginning, the 2ndHealth version of the Worker Health Chartbook was intended to permit access and dissemination of contents to the maximum extent possible. In addition to a print version, NIOSH developed a website based on the content of the 2nd Chartbook. Our intent was to increase both access and availability of the content to the user community. The web version permits visitors to copy text, download the actual charts (*.gif format) and tables, link to external sources based on the extensively documented tables and references, and appendices. The Worker Health eChartbook (hereafter eChartbook) is a continuation of these previous efforts. Begun in late 2005, a small cadre of staff has been developing the new Worker Health eChartbook primarily as a web-based occupational safety and health statistics resources. Many of the features associated with the 2nd Worker Health Chartbook (see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2004-146/) are found here, with the exception of a print document. The current contents include more than 18,000 figures and tables describing the magnitude, distribution, and trends of the Nation\'s occupational injuries, illnesses, and fatalities. In 2011 we plan to expand the resource to include more extensive listing of morbidity and mortality data (chapter 4), state-specific content, as well as general population health status and risk. Also, work is proceeding to develop and include content economics and quality of work life. The eChartbook will continue to grow and develop to reflect the growing data and information needs of the NIOSH Program Portfolio (see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/programs/). We encourage input from all who visit the website. Feel free to send us your questions, feedback, and suggestions for additional content.',`webResource`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return tool35;

Coding schemes are included for: the Nature of the injury or illness; the Part of Body Affected by the injury or illness; the Source and Secondary Source of the injury or illness; and the Event or Exposure. NIOSH has developed this web site and the accompanying downloadable software application as a resource for occupational safety and health researchers, policy makers, employers, and others who may need to use the OIICS for uniformly characterizing occupational injuries and illnesses or better understanding the national occupational injury and illness data released by the BLS and NIOSH (see About OIICS). To code or use the OIICS coded data one should properly understand the OIICS Coding Selection Rules. This site provides a graphical tree interface for each of the four unique coding schemes for OIICS v1.01 and v2.01. The coding trees are searchable and include descriptive details. The complete OIICS manual is viewable as a separate document. In addition, standalone software versions of the coding trees are available for download and installation on your own computer desktop. MERGE (tool38:`Tool`{`id`:'TL38',`name`:'PRAMS: C PONDER [Companion PRAMS Online Data for Epidemiologic Reporting]',`fullName`:'PRAMS: C PONDER [Companion PRAMS Online Data for Epidemiologic Reporting]',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'CPONDER is a Web-based query system created to access data collected through Pregnancy Risk Assessment Monitoring System (PRAMS) surveys. Users have the ability to design their own analysis by choosing from an indexed list of available categorical variables. Descriptive statistics in the form of proportions are included in the resulting report and corresponding graph. CPONDER contains PRAMS data from 2000 through 2006 for state/year combinations that achieve at least a 70% response rate. CPONDER contains 2007 and 2008 data for PRAMS state/year combinations that achieve at least a 65% response rate. As additional years of data are weighted, they will be added to the system. The system indexes 54 variables by topic for selection as the outcome variable in the analyses. In addition, there are 12 control variables for use in breaking out or stratifying the requested analysis— only one break-out variable at a time may be specified. Analyses may be for a single state and year, for a single state and all available years, or for all available states and a single year. With the all available states and a single year analyses, no further break-outs are possible.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/prams/CPONDER.htm',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return tool38;
MERGE (tool39:`Tool`{`id`:'TL39',`name`:'PRAMS: PONDER [PRAMS Online Data for Epidemiologic Reporting]',`fullName`:'PRAMS: PONDER [PRAMS Online Data for Epidemiologic Reporting]',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'PRAMS, the Pregnancy Risk Assessment Monitoring System, is a surveillance project of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and state health departments. PRAMS collects state-specific, population-based data on maternal attitudes and experiences before, during, and shortly after pregnancy. PRAMS was initiated in 1987 because infant mortality rates were no longer declining as rapidly as they had in prior years. In addition, the incidence of low birth weight infants had changed little in the previous 20 years. Research has indicated that maternal behaviors during pregnancy may influence infant birth weight and mortality rates. The goal of the PRAMS project is to improve the health of mothers and infants by reducing adverse outcomes such as low birth weight, infant mortality and morbidity, and maternal morbidity. PRAMS provides state-specific data for planning and assessing health programs and for describing maternal experiences that may contribute to maternal and infant health. PONDER, a web-based query system located on the Inside PRAMS website that is available to CDC and state project staff. PONDER includes weighted data from the PRAMS questionnaire and provides real-time prevalence estimates and robust standard errors through a user friendly, web-enabled, point and click interface. PONDER enables users to perform cross tabulations and generate basic descriptive statistics (e.g., means, weighted and raw counts). Cigarette smoking and exposure to tobacco smoke resulted in at least 443,000 premature deaths, approximately 5.1 million years of potential life lost (YPLL), and $96.8 billion in productivity losses annually in the United States (CDC, 2008). Since 1987, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has used the Smoking-Attributable Mortality, Morbidity, and Economic Costs (SAMMEC) application to estimate the disease impact of smoking for the nation, states, and large populations. The SAMMEC application has been used to estimate smoking-attributable mortality (SAM), YPLL, direct medical expenditures, and productivity losses. However, the primary focus of SAMMEC has been to measure the deaths and years of life lost due to smoking. These estimates were based on an attributable-fraction methodology that applies current information on cigarette smoking prevalence to scientific data on the relative risk of death from diseases shown to be caused by smoking. Estimates are necessary in the absence of adequate information on death certificates about the smoking history of individuals.',`webResource`:'http://apps.nccd.cdc.gov/sammec/index.asp',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return tool47;

National and state-specific information is reported in the State Indicator Report for behavioral indicators and policy and environmental indicators. The policy and environmental indicators are from multiple data sources and measure several aspects of a state\'s ability to support the consumption of F and V. Each indicator can be measured in most states. MERGE (tool57:`Tool`{`id`:'TL57',`name`:'Web-based Injury Statistics Query and Reporting System',`fullName`:'Web-based Injury Statistics Query and Reporting System',`shortName`:'WISQARS',`purpose`:'An interactive Internet-based injury data system. This system markedly increases the speed and efficiency by which users can obtain important injury data for research, prevention program needs, and decision-making purposes. WISQARS eliminates the need for time-consuming computer programming to obtain requested information. Both internal and external users can obtain the data they need via the internet in the format that meets their needs. WISQARS provides current data (e.g., numbers, rates, age-adjusted rates) on fatal and nonfatal injuries. Fatal data are from death certificate data from NVSS of NCHS. The first year of available NVSS death data is 1981. Nonfatal data are from the National Electronic Injury Surveillance System-All Injury Program. The first year of available nonfatal data is 2000. WISQARS also provides data on violent deaths from the National Violence Death Reporting System. The first year of available NVDRS violent death data is 2003. WISQARS also has a new module that provides color choropleth county-level maps of death rates by mechanism and intent of injury and a module that provides lifetime cost of injury data for injury deaths, hospitalizations, and emergency department visits. A WISQARS mobile application is being developed for tablets and smart phones.  This app will provides ready access to injury-related deaths and death rates by selected mechanism and intent in maps, charts and graphs on mobile devices. WISQARS will be adding a new module called “Cost of Injury Reports” on February 24, 2011.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/injury/wisqars/',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return tool57;

MERGE (tool97:`Tool`{`id`:'TL97',`name`:'Metropolitan Atlanta Developmental Disabilities',`fullName`:'Metropolitan Atlanta Developmental Disabilities',`shortName`:'MADD',`purpose`:'To address the problem of developmental disabilities among children, CDC initiated the Metropolitan Atlanta Developmental Disabilities Study (MADDS) in 1984. For this study, which was conducted in Atlanta during 1984-1990, investigators devised methods for determining the prevalence of intellectual disability, cerebral palsy, legal blindness, hearing loss, and epilepsy among children 10 years of age. Children who had these conditions were identified by searching record systems of sources that were likely to contain information relating to the evaluation or treatment of children with developmental disabilities (e.g., schools, hospitals, and state programs for persons who have developmental disabilities). The majority of the children were identified through special education departments within the Atlanta area public school systems. The success of this study prompted CDC to establish the Metropolitan Atlanta Developmental Disabilities Surveillance Program (MADDSP) in 1991, an ongoing system for monitoring the occurrence of selected developmental disabilities. MADDSP is located at CDC in the Developmental Disabilities Branch within the National Center on Birth Defects and Developmental Disabilities. The two principal objectives of MADDSP are to a) provide regular and systematic monitoring of the prevalence of selected developmental disabilities according to various demographic characteristics of children and their mothers and b) provide a framework for initiating special studies of children who have the selected developmental disabilities by establishing a population-based case series of such children. Currently, MADDSP monitors intellectual disability, cerebral palsy, hearing loss, vision impairment and autism spectrum disorders.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/developmentaldisabilities/MADDSP.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1991',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'5 counties of metropolitan Atlanta: Clayton, Cobb, DeKalb, Fulton and Gwinnett',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'10/1/2014',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:'Tom Savel'}) return tool97;

FTP is built on a client-server architecture and uses separate control and data connections between the client and the server.[1] FTP users may authenticate themselves using a clear-text sign-in protocol, normally in the form of a username and password, but can connect anonymously if the server is configured to allow it. For secure transmission that protects the username and password, and encrypts the content, FTP is often secured with SSL/TLS (FTPS). SSH File Transfer Protocol (SFTP) is sometimes also used instead, but is technologically different. MERGE (tool101:`Tool`{`id`:'TL101',`name`:'Electronic Disease Notification',`fullName`:'Electronic Disease Notification',`shortName`:'EDN',`purpose`:'Approximately 450,000 legal permanent immigrants and 75,000 refugees enter the United States annually after receiving required medical examinations by overseas panel physicians (physicians who follow the CDC medical screening guidelines provided to the U.S. Department of State). CDC has the regulatory responsibility for preventing the introduction, transmission, and spread of communicable diseases into the United States as well as for developing the guidelines, known as technical instructions, for the overseas medical examinations. Other conditions that are not infectious might preclude an immigrant or refugee from entering the United States and also are reported as part of the medical examination. After arrival in the United States, all refugees are recommended to obtain a medical assessment by a health-care provider or a health department within 30 days. In addition, immigrants with certain medical conditions such as noninfectious tuberculosis at the time of the original medical examination are recommended to be evaluated after arrival to ensure that appropriate prevention or treatment measures are instituted. Health departments need timely and accurate notifications of newly arriving immigrants, refugees, and persons with other visa types to facilitate these evaluations.
