MERGE (reg4:`Registry`{`id`:'RG4',`name`:'International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research',`fullName`:'International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research',`shortName`:'',`registryType`:'',`purpose`:'The International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research (ICBDSR, or Clearinghouse in short) is a voluntary nonprofit International Organization affiliated with WHO. The Organization brings together birth defect surveillance and research programs from around the world with the aim of investigating and preventing birth defects and lessening the impact of their consequences. The Organization was first established in 1974, at a meeting in Helsinki, Finland, where representatives of malformation registries in ten countries were present. It was named the International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Monitoring Systems (ICBDMS) and member programs were actively engaged in the systematic collection and analysis of data for the comprehensive monitoring of congenital malformations. In 2003/4, a strategic planning group was set up with the aim of suggesting new strategic goals for the Organization. These suggestions were approved at the Clearinghouse Annual Meeting in Japan, 2004 and the Organization under the current name of International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research (ICBDSR), was officially established. It now has 44 member programs worldwide. The mission of the International Clearinghouse of Birth Defects Surveillance and Research is to conduct worldwide surveillance and research into the occurrence and possible causes of Birth Defects with the aim of preventing them and decreasing their consequences. The strategic priority of the Clearinghouse is to conduct worldwide surveillance and to exchange data about birth defects. The scope of the Clearinghouse includes fetal and childhood conditions of prenatal cause. Participating surveillance programs will carry out systematic data collection and use the data for public health action. Public health action includes comparing prevalence rates, advocacy, policy development, conducting epidemiological studies of causes and consequences of birth defects, assessing preventive and therapeutic interventions, and interacting with the public, research institutions and relevant government agencies.',`webResource`:'http://www.icbdsr.org',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1974',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'5 counties of metropolitan Atlanta: Clayton, Cobb, Dekalb, Fulton, and Gwinett',`dataProvidersManual`:'',`dataProvidersElectronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipientsManual`:'',`dataRecipientsElectronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Members Of General Public, State / Territorial Health Departments, Schools / Universities',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`avrCapability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return reg4;

It collects data on the occurrence of cancer; the type, extent, and location of the cancer; and the type of initial treatment. NPCR supports central cancer registries in 45 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Pacific Island Jurisdictions. These data represent 96% of the U.S. population. In each U.S. state, DC, and territory, local and regional cancer data are reported to central cancer registries about all new diagnoses of cancer from patient records at such medical facilities as hospitals, physicians\'offices, therapeutic radiation facilities, freestanding surgical centers, and pathology laboratories. These data are submitted annually in November to CDC’s NPCR. Data collected by local cancer registries enable public health professionals to understand and address the cancer burden more effectively. Since its inception in 2002, the registry has evolved into the largest post disaster follow-up in US history and is recognized as the primary source for epidemiological findings regarding the effects of 9-11 related exposures for both physical and mental health disease. Peer reviewed objective and scientifically valid data from the registry on the long term health burden of 9-11 has resulted in continued medical monitoring and treatment of 9-11 rescue/recovery workers, lower Manhattan residents, and children who were enrolled in schools in the vicinity of WTC. The registry has also been used by external researchers who have completed studies in such areas as building evacuation safety and procedures and biological basis for Post traumatic stress disorder. MERGE (colla2:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO2',`name`:'Biosurveillance Coordination Activity',`fullName`:'Biosurveillance Coordination Activity',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'In 2007, Homeland Security Presidential Directive 21 (HSPD-21) was issued in recognition of the emergence of significant health-related threats to the nation. HSPD-21 called for the development of a nationwide approach to biosurveillance in order to enhance the United States’ ability to detect and respond to those threats. HSPD-21 defines biosurveillance as— …the process of active data-gathering with appropriate analysis and interpretation of biosphere data that might relate to disease activity and threats to human or animal health—whether infectious, toxic, metabolic, or otherwise, and regardless or intentional or natural origin—in order to achieve early warning of health threats, early detection of health events, and overall situational awareness of disease activity. The Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) was charged with the responsibility of enhancing biosurveillance for human health and delegated this responsibility to CDC. In 2008, CDC established the Biosurveillance Coordination unit (BC) to oversee the necessary activities to address these mandates. With input from federal, state, local, tribal, and private stakeholders, the BC unit coordinated the release of the first draft version of the National Biosurveillance Strategy for Human Health (NBSHH) in December 2008. The NBSHH established priorities for the nation’s next-generation biosurveillance capability to provide timely, comprehensive, and accessible information to strengthen public health practice, provide value to clinicians, and build upon current systems and resources. Version 2 of the National Biosurveillance Strategy for Human Health (NBSHH) was extensively revised and expanded to include additional information. It was released in February 2010.',`webResource`:'',`operationStartDate`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`collaborativeParticipants`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`dataProvidersManual`:'',`dataProvidersElectronic`:'',`dataRecipientsManual`:'',`dataRecipientsElectronic`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`startDateGeneration`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return colla2;

The FETP itself was modeled after CDC\'s Epidemic Intelligence Service. FELTPs help support CDC\'s global health diplomacy by fostering close partnerships with MOHs, U.S. diplomatic facilities abroad, and international agencies. FELTPs promote epidemiology and public health laboratory collaboration by providing joint epidemiology laboratory leadership and management training, including public health laboratorians in field investigations; using laboratory data for disease surveillance; and improving biosafety and quality assurance control in specimen collection and transport, laboratory analysis, reporting, and interpretation.',`webResource`:'',`operationStartDate`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`collaborativeParticipants`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`dataProvidersManual`:'',`dataProvidersElectronic`:'',`dataRecipientsManual`:'',`dataRecipientsElectronic`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`startDateGeneration`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return colla4;

A sensitive and specific IgM antibody assay was developed to assist in the laboratory confirmation of suspected measles cases. In addition, viral isolates were collected for genetic analysis and characterization. The information from the characterization of viruses analyzed during the 1989-1991 resurgence of measles and the ongoing viral surveillance throughout the 1990s was important data that helped to document the elimination of endemic transmission of measles in the United States. Responsibility for rubella and mumps viruses was transferred to the Measles Virus Section in 1997-1998. The current Rubella Virus Laboratory was formed in 1998 in the measles section. After a major reorganization the rubella laboratory team was officially moved to the Measles, Mumps, Rubella (MMR) and Herpesvirus Laboratory Branch (MMRHLB), Division of Viral Diseases, National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases. The Rubella Laboratory provides serologic and molecular testing for rubella as a national reference laboratory and provides technical assistance to state public health laboratories for the collection and shipment of clinical samples for rubella RT-PCR and sequencing. The Rubella Laboratory team works with the Epidemiology Branch to coordinate laboratory support for local and state public health laboratories during outbreaks and investigations of suspected spread cases following an importation of rubella. The OutbreakNet Team works in partnership with US State and local health departments, the US Department of Agriculture (USDA), the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA), and PulseNet (a national surveillance network made up of state and local public health laboratories and federal food regulatory agency laboratories that perform pulsed-field gel electrophoresis on bacteria that may be foodborne). MERGE (colla18:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO18',`name`:'Pediatric Bacterial Meningitis Surveillance Network',`fullName`:'Pediatric Bacterial Meningitis Surveillance Network',`shortName`:'PBMS',`purpose`:'The WHO/AFRO Pediatric Bacterial Meningitis (PBM) surveillance network was established in 2001 to assist countries in the African region to establish a baseline of data on the burden of invasive bacterial disease for new vaccine introduction as well as in the monitoring of new vaccine programs. MERGE (colla24:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO24',`name`:'Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology',`fullName`:'Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology',`shortName`:'ROGUE',`purpose`:'The purpose of Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology (ROGUE) working group was to 1) Reduce the number of foodborne illnesses with unknown etiology and 2) Provide epidemiologic and laboratory assistance when possible. The Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology (ROGUE) working group investigates foodborne diseases that may have a chemical etiology. Since the most common foodborne illnesses are due to biological organisms, these are much more commonly considered early in an outbreak. Recognition of chemical etiologies is often not made until later, and this hinders ultimate identification of responsible agents because of the timeliness with which samples must be collected. Better clues are needed to help clinicians and public health officials determine if a foodborne outbreak may have a chemical etiology. People that become ill from chemical contaminants in food may comment that the food had an unusual taste, smell or appearance. These organoleptic qualities can be important clues in identifying the types of agents that may have contaminated the food and caused illness, as well as helpful in identifying that a chemical induced foodborne illness may be occurring. Unfortunately, in the investigation of foodborne illness complaints, this type of information is seldom collected in a uniform manner.',`webResource`:'',`operationStartDate`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Retired',`collaborativeParticipants`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`dataProvidersManual`:'',`dataProvidersElectronic`:'',`dataRecipientsManual`:'',`dataRecipientsElectronic`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'No',`startDateGeneration`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`informationValidatedBy`:'',`informationValidatedOn`:'',`lastUpdatedBy`:''}) return colla24;

MERGE (colla28:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO28',`name`:'WHO Collaborating Center for Rotavirus and the Agents of Viral Gastroenteritis',`fullName`:'WHO Collaborating Center for Rotavirus and the Agents of Viral Gastroenteritis',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'CDC’s - Rotavirus Program serves as a World Health Organization (WHO) Collaborating Center for rotavirus and other viral agents of gastroenteritis. WHO designated the Rotavirus Program a Collaborating Center beginning in 1998 and redesignation occurs every five years. The primary role of the CDC Rotavirus Collaborating Center is to support the WHO Global Rotavirus Surveillance Network that collects data on rotavirus disease burden and strain prevalence as part of efforts to introduce rotavirus vaccines globally. Globally, rotavirus is the cause of about  450,000 diarrheal deaths every year,  almost all of which occur in  developing countries. In addition, many more children will get dehydrated and require medical intervention and hospitalization. Several vaccines against rotavirus have been, or are being, developed to reduce this burden. Since 2006, two live attenuated vaccines against rotavirus have been licensed in more than 100 countries around the world and are now recommended by WHO for global use. One component of efforts to introduce rotavirus vaccines globally is the derivation of global, regional and local disease burden and strain prevalence estimates to help make the case for vaccination and to support countries decisions about rotavirus vaccine introduction.. The CDC and WHO have developed a generic protocol for standardized surveillance of rotavirus disease burden and strain prevalence, and with support from the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization (GAVI) and in collaboration with CDC and country partners, WHO has recently developed a Global Rotavirus Surveillance Network made up of regional networks (about 60 countries) in the six WHO regions (Americas, Africa, European, Eastern Mediterranean, Southeast Asia and Western Pacific Regions) to collect current data.  The role of the CDC Rotavirus Program and its Collaborating Center is to provide the WHO with technical expertise and laboratory and epidemiologic support to aid in network activities. Another Rotavirus Collaborating Center from Melbourne, Australia and Rotavirus Reference Laboratories from the six WHO regions provide region-specific laboratory support. Terms of reference of the center: 1. To conduct evaluations of rotavirus vaccines in collaboration with the Department of Vaccines and Biologicals (V&B, WHO) and developing country investigators. 2. To conduct rotavirus disease and strain surveillance with support from the Childhood Vaccine Program, Program of Appropriate Technology in Health (PATH) of the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, and V&B, WHO 3. To serve as a vaccine evaluation training center for scientists for developing and developed countries. 4. MERGE (datastd14:`DataStandard`{`id`:'DSTD14',`name`:'Diagnosis-Related Group',`terminologyShortName`:'',`terminologyFullName`:'',`description`:'Diagnosis-related group (DRG) is a system to classify hospital cases into one of originally 467 groups,with the 467th group being \"Ungroupable\". This system of classification was developed as a collaborative project by Robert B Fetter, PhD, of the Yale School of Management, and John D. Thompson, MPH, of the Yale School of Public Health.The system is also referred to as \"the DRGs\", and its intent was to identify the \"products\" that a hospital provides. One example of a \"product\" is an appendectomy. The system was developed in anticipation of convincing Congress to use it for reimbursement, to replace \"cost based\" reimbursement that had been used up to that point. DRGs are assigned by a \"grouper\" program based on ICD (International Classification of Diseases) diagnoses, procedures, age, sex, discharge status, and the presence of complications or comorbidities. DRGs have been used in the US since 1982 to determine how much Medicare pays the hospital for each \"product\", since patients within each category are clinically similar and are expected to use the same level of hospital resources.DRGs may be further grouped into Major Diagnostic Categories (MDCs). DRGs are also standard practice for establishing reimbursements for other Medicare related reimbursements such as to home healthcare providers.',`terminoloyID`:'',`terminologyVersionNumber`:'',`licenseType`:'',`referenceURL`:'',`notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:'Yes',`informationValidatedBy`:'Tom Savel',`informationValidatedOn`:'9/30/2014',`lastUpdatedBy`:'Tom Savel'}) return datastd14;

MERGE (datastd24:`DataStandard`{`id`:'DSTD24',`name`:'SOC',`terminologyShortName`:'',`terminologyFullName`:'',`description`:'The Standard Occupational Classification (SOC) System is a United States government system of classifying occupations. It is used by U.S. federal government agencies collecting occupational data, enabling comparison of occupations across data sets. It is designed to cover all occupations in which work is performed for pay or profit, reflecting the current occupational structure in the United States. The 2010 SOC includes 840 occupational types.   Users of occupational data include government program managers, industrial and labor relations practitioners, students considering career training, job seekers, vocational training schools, and employers wishing to set salary scales or locate a new plant.   The SOC codes have a hierarchical format, so for example the code \"15-0000\" refers to occupations in the \"Computer and Mathematical Occupations\" category, and \"15-1130\" is a subset for \"Software Developers and Programmers.\"    The SOC does not categorize industries or employers. There are orthogonal category systems for industries used with SOC data, most commonly NAICS.
